		 Thursday, March 18, 2004  Nation at a Glance				 																SC to hear Advani yatra ban plea				 																																																	New Delhi: The Supreme Court will on Thursday hear a petition seeking a ban on deputy Prime Minister L.K. Advanis Bharat Uday yatra, reports our legal correspondent.				 																																																										Advocate S.Veeraraghavan, whose petition had been dismissed by Madras High Court, moved the apex court on Wednesday seeking a directive to stop the yatra on the ground that it is likely to create communal tension.				 																																																										After the high court dismissed the petition, Veeraraghavan moved the apex court with a special leave petition against the order. 				 																																																										A similar petition was also dismissed by Delhi High Court on Wednesday.				 																																																	he petitioner before Delhi High Court, Shyamdev Bhadana, an Intuc secretary, was told to approach the Election Commission. The high court said: We are not inclined to entertain this petition and the petitioners are directed to approach the Election Commission.				 																Paper leak stalls BCom exam				 																																																	Mumbai: Mumbai University was forced to postpone its accounts paper for the third-year BCom exam after reports came in that students had bought it just like they buy chaat masala outside the college gates for as little as Rs 1,000, reports our correspondent.				 																																																										The question papers were reportedly available three days before the examination on Wednesday. 				 																																																										Rumours that question papers had been leaked started on Saturday, the day the BCom final year exam started.				 																																																										The university had managed to change the auditing paper at the last moment and conduct the test as scheduled on Tuesday. But we could not rush in an alternative paper today (Wednesday), a source said.				 																																																										The eight-page paper had nine questions. Sources said students who had bought the papers knew all the questions.				 																																																	rom this year, the university has given the work of distributing the papers to a private agency. An education ministry official said: We get a private agency to distribute the papers so that chances of a leak are minimised and we find out that they are being sold like chana at the college gates.				 																																																										This has to be an inside job. We have taken this very seriously and will soon get to the guilty.				 																Riot accused denied bail				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court on Wednesday rejected the bail plea of Maulana Hussain Ibrahim Umarji, a key accused in the Sabarmati Express carnage at Godhra on February 27, 2002. A bench of Justices S. Rajendra Babu, Arun Kumar and G.P. Mathur upheld the Gujarat High Court order refusing to grant him bail.				 																																																										Umarji was arrested by the police under the IPC. Later, the anti-terror law was invoked against him. 				 																Detainee set free				 																																																	Nagpur (PTI): Three policemen were booked for allegedly helping a Mcoca detainee visit his house on the pretext of a medical check up, police said. Anil Dhjawde, detained under the Maharashtra Control of Organised Crime Act and lodged in the central prison, was planning to escape with the help of the policemen escorting him to the hospital. But the crime branch raided his home and nabbed him and his police accomplices arrested. 				 																Extradition nod				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): A Hong Kong court has allowed the extradition of Ashok Tabilram Sadarangani, allegedly involved in forgeries at two banks in India amounting to Rs 84.55 million. CBI sources said they received a communique from Interpol, Hong Kong. The bureau will soon send a team to bring back the fugitive. 				 																Sons kill father				 																																																	Muzaffarnagar (PTI): A man was allegedly beaten to death by two of his sons over a minor dispute. Police said Harilal Singh, 55, was beaten by his sons after they had a quarrel with two other brothers over sharing tubewell water for irrigation.				 																Five killed				 																																																	Bhabhua (PTI): At least five persons were killed and 20 injured when a tractor trolley plunged into a ditch in Bihars Kaimur district. The accident took place after the driver lost control of the vehicle.				 																Child death				 																																																	Salem (PTI): A child and another passenger were killed and 35 injured when a bus fell into a 100-foot gorge near here. The bus was coming from Kolli Hills to Salem when the mishap occurred. 																		The Rajasthan government is holding a training camp for priests for the first time in the state. Over 70 priests are attending the camp organised by the devasthan department. The camp is being held to ensure that Hindu traditions are followed adequately.
